.TH "WORKER.WORKER" "3JS" "January 26, 2026" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Worker.Worker \- Worker: Worker() constructor
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]Note:\f[R] This feature is available in Web Workers, except for
Service Workers.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Warning:\f[R] This script passed to the \f[CR]url\f[R] element is
executed.
APIs like this are known as injection sinks, and are potentially a
vector for cross\-site scripting (XSS) attacks.
.PP
You can mitigate this risk by having a Content Security Policy (CSP)
that restricts the locations from which scripts can be loaded, and by
always assigning \f[CR]TrustedScriptURL\f[R] objects instead of strings
and enforcing trusted types.
See Security considerations for more information.
.RE
.PP
The \f[B]\f[CB]Worker()\f[B]\f[R] constructor creates a
\f[CR]Worker\f[R] object that executes the classic script or module at
the specified URL.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
new Worker(url)
new Worker(url, options)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]url\f[R]
A \f[CR]TrustedScriptURL\f[R] object or a string representing the URL of
the script or module that the worker will execute.
.RS
.PP
This must be same\-origin with the caller\(cqs document, or a
\f[CR]blob:\f[R] or \f[CR]data:\f[R] URL.
The URL is resolved relative to the current HTML page\(cqs location.
.RE
.TP
\f[B]options\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
An object containing option properties that can be set when creating the
object instance.
Available properties are as follows:
.RS
.TP
\f[B]credentials\f[R]
A string specifying whether the browser sends credentials when importing
modules into a module worker.
The allowed values are the same as can be passed to the
\f[CR]fetch()\f[R] request: \f[CR]omit\f[R], \f[CR]same\-origin\f[R], or
\f[CR]include\f[R].
The default is \f[CR]same\-origin\f[R] (only include credentials for
same\-origin requests).
.RS
.PP
This is ignored for classic workers.
.RE
.TP
\f[B]name\f[R]
A string specifying an identifying name for the
\f[CR]DedicatedWorkerGlobalScope\f[R] representing the scope of the
worker, which is mainly useful for debugging purposes.
.TP
\f[B]type\f[R]
A string specifying the type of worker to create.
The value can be \f[CR]classic\f[R] or \f[CR]module\f[R].
The default is \f[CR]classic\f[R].
.RE
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]NetworkError\f[R] \f[B]DOMException\f[R]
Thrown if the MIME type of the worker script is incorrect.
It \f[I]should\f[R] always be \f[CR]text/javascript\f[R] (for historical
reasons other JavaScript MIME types may be accepted).
.TP
\f[B]SecurityError\f[R] \f[B]DOMException\f[R]
Thrown if the document is not allowed to start workers, e.g., if the URL
has an invalid syntax or if the same\-origin policy is violated.
.TP
\f[B]SyntaxError\f[R] \f[B]DOMException\f[R]
Thrown if \f[CR]url\f[R] cannot be parsed.
.TP
\f[B]TypeError\f[R]
Thrown if the \f[CR]url\f[R] parameter is a string when Trusted Types
are enforced by a CSP and no default policy is defined.
.SH DESCRIPTION
The \f[B]\f[CB]Worker()\f[B]\f[R] constructor creates a
\f[CR]Worker\f[R] object that executes the classic script or module at
the specified URL.
.PP
The script must be same\-origin with the associated document, but may
itself import scripts or modules that are cross\-origin (if permitted by
CORS and other restrictions).
If a cross\-origin worker is required, users must load it from an
intermediate same\-origin worker or a blob.
.SS Module and classic workers
A classic worker is one that that is constructed from a classic script,
while a module worker is constructed from an ECMASCript module.
The type of worker affects the worker constructor options, how the
worker script is fetched, and how it is executed.
.PP
The code below shows two ways you can construct a classic worker, and
also how you specify the \f[CR]type\f[R] of \f[CR]\(dqmodule\(dq\f[R] to
create a module worker.
In both cases the script must be same\-origin with the loading document
and is resolved relative to the location of the launching document.
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// Construct a classic worker\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] worker1 = \f[B]new\f[R] Worker(\(dqworker_classic.js\(dq);
\f[B]const\f[R] worker2 = \f[B]new\f[R] Worker(\(dqworker_classic.js\(dq, {
  type: \(dqclassic\(dq,
});

\f[I]// Construct a module worker\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] worker3 = \f[B]new\f[R] Worker(\(dqworker_module.js\(dq, {
  type: \(dqmodule\(dq,
});
.EE
.PP
Module workers and their dependencies are loaded and executed using
ECMAScript module semantics:
.IP \(bu 2
Dependencies are imported via static \f[CR]import\f[R] statements
.IP \(bu 2
Fetched asynchronously using CORS.
.IP \(bu 2
All modules are resolved before any code is executed
.IP \(bu 2
Must be served with the media type
\f[CR]Content\-Type: text/javascript\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
Executed in Strict mode
.PP
Classic workers are fetched and executed as scripts:
.IP \(bu 2
Dependencies are imported using the
\f[CR]WorkerGlobalScope.importScripts()\f[R] method
.IP \(bu 2
Fetched synchronously in \f[CR]no\-cors\f[R] mode
.SS Importing scripts or modules
Module workers can import ECMASCript modules using \f[CR]import\f[R]
statements.
Modules are fetched using CORS, so cross\-origin modules must be served
with the \f[CR]Access\-Control\-Allow\-Origin\f[R] header in order to be
loaded.
Developers can specify whether or not credentials should be sent in
cross\-origin imports.
.PP
Classic workers can import scripts (but not modules) using the
\f[CR]WorkerGlobalScope.importScripts()\f[R] method.
Unlike modules, scripts are fetched in \f[CR]no\-cors\f[R] mode, and can
be requested cross\-origin even if the server does not set the
appropriate CORS headers.
Credentials are sent for same\-origin imports, but are usually not sent
for cross\-origin requests.
.PP
In addition, if the document has a Content Security Policy (CSP), it
must allow the origins of imported scripts or modules.
For modules the allowed sources are specified in \f[CR]worker\-src\f[R]
(with fallback to \f[CR]script\-src\f[R] and \f[CR]default\-src\f[R]
directives), while for classic scripts the sources are specified in
\f[CR]script\-src\f[R] (with fallback to the \f[CR]default\-src\f[R]
directives).
.SS \f[CR]data:\f[R] and \f[CR]blob:\f[R] URLs
\f[CR]data:\f[R] URLs can be passed to the \f[CR]url\f[R] parameter, but
have an opaque_origin, which makes them cross\-origin to all other
origins including their owner.
.PP
Consequently, while the worker can still communicate with its owner
using \f[CR]postMessage()\f[R], it\(cqs access to other external
resources is highly restricted.
For example, a worker \f[CR]fetch()\f[R] request would be cross\-origin
to its own site, and any requests to any origin must be granted by CORS.
.PP
\f[CR]blob:\f[R] URLs should be used instead, where possible, because
the URL inherits the origin of the document that created it.
This ensures that a worker created with a \f[CR]blob:\f[R] URL is
same\-origin with the page that created it.
Note that if you\(cqre using a Content Security Policy (CSP) to restrict
what resources can be loaded into your worker, you will need to allow
the \f[CR]blob:\f[R] origin.
.SS Bundler considerations
Bundlers such as \c
.UR https://webpack.js.org/guides/web-workers/
webpack
.UE \c
, \c
.UR https://vite.dev/guide/features.html#web-workers
Vite
.UE \c
, and \c
.UR https://parceljs.org/languages/javascript/#web-workers
Parcel
.UE \c
, recommend passing URLs that are relative to \f[CR]import.meta.url\f[R]
to the \f[CR]Worker()\f[R] constructor.
.PP
For example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] myWorker = \f[B]new\f[R] Worker(\f[B]new\f[R] URL(\(dqworker.js\(dq, \f[B]import\f[R].meta.url));
.EE
.PP
This makes the path relative to the current script instead of the
current HTML page, which allows the bundler to safely do optimizations
like renaming (because otherwise the \f[CR]worker.js\f[R] URL may point
to a file not controlled by the bundler, so it cannot make any
assumptions).
.SS Security considerations
The script or module specified by the \f[CR]url\f[R] argument is
executed in the web worker context, and may itself import other
same\-origin and cross\-origin scripts.
If the \f[CR]url\f[R] is provided by a user, this is a possible vector
for cross\-site scripting (XSS) attacks.
.PP
While web workers do not have direct access to the owning document or
window, it is still extremely risky to accept and execute arbitrary URLs
from untrusted origins.
For module workers, but not classic workers, CORS will control what
cross\-origin resources can be requested.
.PP
A website should also control what scripts that are allowed to run using
a Content Security Policy (CSP) with the \f[CR]worker\-src\f[R]
directive (or a fallback to \f[CR]child\-src\f[R],
\f[CR]script\-src\f[R], or \f[CR]default\-src\f[R]).
This can restrict scripts to those from the current origin, or a
specific set of origins, or even particular files.
.PP
If you\(cqre using this property and enforcing trusted types (using the
\f[CR]require\-trusted\-types\-for\f[R] CSP directive), you will need to
always assign \f[CR]TrustedScriptURL\f[R] objects instead of strings.
This ensures that the input is passed through a transformation function,
which has the chance to reject or modify URLs needed by the worker
before they are fetched.
.SH EXAMPLES
For brevity, only the first example below uses trusted types.
In production your code should always use trusted types when passing
data originating from users into injection sinks.
.SS Using Trusted Types
To mitigate the risk of XSS, we should always pass
\f[CR]TrustedScriptURL\f[R] instances to the worker URL instead of
strings.
We also need to do this if we\(cqre enforcing trusted types for other
reasons and we want to allow some sources that have been permitted (by
\f[CR]CSP: worker\-src\f[R]).
.PP
Trusted types are not yet supported on all browsers, so first we define
the trusted types tinyfill.
This acts as a transparent replacement for the trusted types JavaScript
API:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]if\f[R] (\f[B]typeof\f[R] trustedTypes === \(dqundefined\(dq)
  trustedTypes = { createPolicy: (n, rules) \f[B]=>\f[R] rules };
.EE
.PP
Next we create a \f[CR]TrustedTypePolicy\f[R] that defines a
\f[CR]createScriptURL()\f[R] method for transforming input strings into
\f[CR]TrustedScriptURL\f[R] instances.
.PP
For the purpose of this example we\(cqll assume that we want to allow a
predefined set of URLs in the \f[CR]workerScriptAllowList\f[R] array and
log any other scripts.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] workerScriptAllowList = [
  \f[I]// Some list of allowed URLs\f[R]
];
\f[B]const\f[R] policy = trustedTypes.createPolicy(\(dqworker\-url\-policy\(dq, {
  createScriptURL(input) {
    \f[B]if\f[R] (workerScriptAllowList.includes(input)) {
      \f[B]return\f[R] input; \f[I]// allow the script\f[R]
    }
    console.log(\(gaScript not in workerScriptAllowList: ${input}\(ga);
    \f[B]return\f[R] \(dq\(dq; \f[I]// Block the script\f[R]
  },
});
.EE
.PP
Next we use our \f[CR]policy\f[R] object to create a
\f[CR]trustedScriptURL\f[R] object from a potentially unsafe input
string and pass this to the worker.
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// The potentially malicious worker URL\f[R]
\f[I]// We won\(aqt be including untrustedScript in our workerScriptAllowList array\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] untrustedScriptURL = \(dqhttps://evil.example.com/naughty.js\(dq;

\f[I]// Create a TrustedScriptURL instance using the policy\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] trustedScriptURL = policy.createScriptURL(untrustedScriptURL);

\f[I]// Construct the worker with the trusted URL\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] myWorker = \f[B]new\f[R] Worker(trustedScriptURL);
.EE
.SS Creating a classic worker
The following code snippet shows creation of a classic \f[CR]Worker\f[R]
object using the \f[CR]Worker()\f[R] constructor, and subsequent usage
of the object:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] myWorker = \f[B]new\f[R] Worker(\(dqworker.js\(dq);
\f[B]const\f[R] first = document.querySelector(\(dqinput#number1\(dq);

first.onchange = () \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  myWorker.postMessage(first.value);
  console.log(\(dqMessage posted to worker\(dq);
};
.EE
.PP
For a full example, see our \c
.UR https://github.com/mdn/dom-examples/tree/main/web-workers/simple-web-worker
Basic dedicated worker example
.UE \c
\ (\c
.UR https://mdn.github.io/dom-examples/web-workers/simple-web-worker/
run dedicated worker
.UE \c
).
.SS Loading a cross\-origin module worker from a blob
This example shows a method that can fetch and load a cross\-origin
module worker script and then load it into your worker as a blob (a
classic script could be loaded in the same way):
.IP
.EX
\f[B]async\f[R] \f[B]function\f[R] loadWorker() {
  \f[B]const\f[R] response = \f[B]await\f[R] fetch(\(dqhttps://other_origin.com/worker.js\(dq);
  \f[B]const\f[R] script = \f[B]await\f[R] response.text();

  \f[I]// Create a blob that contains the fetched script, and then create a URL from that blob\f[R]
  \f[B]const\f[R] blob = \f[B]new\f[R] Blob([script], { type: \(dqapplication/javascript\(dq });
  \f[B]const\f[R] workerUrl = URL.createObjectURL(blob);

  \f[B]try\f[R] {
    \f[B]const\f[R] worker = \f[B]new\f[R] Worker(workerUrl, { type: \(dqmodule\(dq });
  } \f[B]catch\f[R] (e) {
    console.error(\(gaCross\-origin worker module failed to load: ${e}\(ga);
  }
}
loadWorker();
.EE
.PP
The initial fetch is made with CORS, and so the
\f[CR]other_origin.com\f[R] response will need to include the
\f[CR]Access\-Control\-Allow\-Origin\f[R] header as shown:
.IP
.EX
Access\-Control\-Allow\-Origin \(dqhttps://my_origin.com\(dq
.EE
.PP
In addition, if you\(cqre using a CSP you will need to allow the
\f[CR]blob:\f[R] origin for \f[CR]worker\-src\f[R] so that it can be
loaded into the document:
.IP
.EX
Content\-Security\-Policy worker\-src \(aqself\(aq https://other_origin.com blob:
.EE
